	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64393386"><p><div class="quote"><p>The fusion reactions are happening basically in high vacuum.</p></div><p>At room temperature, yes.<br>
At 150 million C, the pressure is high enough to breach the coulomb barrier, obviously.</p><p><div class="quote"><p>The amount of fuel is extremely low.</p></div><p>Yes, it is, relatively speaking.</p><p><div class="quote"><p>It is unlikely we will ever have a fusion reactor, that is so big that a failure in the magnetic field, will have negative consequence s to the reactor.</p></div><p>You're probably right, if no reason other than the difficulty getting enough fuel to power one.<br>
100GW is a common cited target, and regardless of fuel in the reactor, 100GW of thermal flux is 100GW of thermal flux.<br>
100GW requires around a kilogram of deuterium and tritium (combined) per day.<br>
At any one time, there's enough shit in that reactor at 150 million degree<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

